.IX Title "TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl 3"
.TH TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl 3 "perl v5.6.2" "2015-01-14" "User Contributed Perl Documentation"
.UC
.SH "NAME"
\&\s-1TAP:\s0:Parser::SourceHandler::Perl \- Stream \s-1TAP\s0 from a Perl executable
.SH "VERSION"
.IX Header "VERSION"
Version 3.35
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.IX Header "SYNOPSIS"
.Vb 2
\&  use TAP::Parser::Source;
\&  use TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl;
.Ve
.Vb 2
\&  my $source = TAP::Parser::Source->new->raw( \e'script.pl' );
\&  $source->assemble_meta;
.Ve
.Vb 3
\&  my $class = 'TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl';
\&  my $vote  = $class->can_handle( $source );
\&  my $iter  = $class->make_iterator( $source );
.Ve
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
This is a \fIPerl\fR the TAP::Parser::SourceHandler manpage \- it has 2 jobs:
.PP
1. Figure out if the the TAP::Parser::Source manpage it's given is actually a Perl
script (the can_handle entry elsewhere in this document).
.PP
2. Creates an iterator for Perl sources (the make_iterator entry elsewhere in this document).
.PP
Unless you're writing a plugin or subclassing the TAP::Parser manpage, you probably
won't need to use this module directly.
.SH "METHODS"
.IX Header "METHODS"
.Sh "Class Methods"
.IX Subsection "Class Methods"
.if n .I "\f(CW""can_handle""\fP"
.el .I "\f(CWcan_handle\fP"
.IX Subsection "can_handle"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  my $vote = $class->can_handle( $source );
.Ve
Only votes if \f(CW$source\fR looks like a file.  Casts the following votes:
.PP
.Vb 6
\&  0.9  if it has a shebang ala "#!...perl"
\&  0.75 if it has any shebang
\&  0.8  if it's a .t file
\&  0.9  if it's a .pl file
\&  0.75 if it's in a 't' directory
\&  0.25 by default (backwards compat)
.Ve
.if n .I "\f(CW""make_iterator""\fP"
.el .I "\f(CWmake_iterator\fP"
.IX Subsection "make_iterator"
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  my $iterator = $class->make_iterator( $source );
.Ve
Constructs & returns a new the TAP::Parser::Iterator::Process manpage for the source.
Assumes \f(CW\*(C`$source\->raw\*(C'\fR contains a reference to the perl script.  \f(CW\*(C`croak\*(C'\fRs
if the file could not be found.
.PP
The command to run is built as follows:
.PP
.Vb 1
\&  $perl @switches $perl_script @test_args
.Ve
The perl command to use is determined by the get_perl entry elsewhere in this document.  The command generated
is guaranteed to preserve:
.PP
.Vb 3
\&  PERL5LIB
\&  PERL5OPT
\&  Taint Mode, if set in the script's shebang
.Ve
\&\fINote:\fR the command generated will \fInot\fR respect any shebang line defined in
your Perl script.  This is only a problem if you have compiled a custom version
of Perl or if you want to use a specific version of Perl for one test and a
different version for another, for example:
.PP
.Vb 2
\&  #!/path/to/a/custom_perl --some --args
\&  #!/usr/local/perl-5.6/bin/perl -w
.Ve
Currently you need to write a plugin to get around this.
.PP
.if n .I "\f(CW""get_taint""\fP"
.el .I "\f(CWget_taint\fP"
.IX Subsection "get_taint"
.PP
Decode any taint switches from a Perl shebang line.
.PP
.Vb 2
\&  # $taint will be 't'
\&  my $taint = TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl->get_taint( '#!/usr/bin/perl -t' );
.Ve
.Vb 2
\&  # $untaint will be undefined
\&  my $untaint = TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl->get_taint( '#!/usr/bin/perl' );
.Ve
.if n .I "\f(CW""get_perl""\fP"
.el .I "\f(CWget_perl\fP"
.IX Subsection "get_perl"
.PP
Gets the version of Perl currently running the test suite.
.SH "SUBCLASSING"
.IX Header "SUBCLASSING"
Please see the SUBCLASSING entry in the TAP::Parser manpage for a subclassing overview.
.Sh "Example"
.IX Subsection "Example"
.Vb 1
\&  package MyPerlSourceHandler;
.Ve
.Vb 1
\&  use strict;
.Ve
.Vb 1
\&  use TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl;
.Ve
.Vb 1
\&  use base 'TAP::Parser::SourceHandler::Perl';
.Ve
.Vb 9
\&  # use the version of perl from the shebang line in the test file
\&  sub get_perl {
\&      my $self = shift;
\&      if (my $shebang = $self->shebang( $self->{file} )) {
\&          $shebang =~ /^#!(.*\ebperl.*?)(?:(?:\es)|(?:$))/;
\&          return $1 if $1;
\&      }
\&      return $self->SUPER::get_perl(@_);
\&  }
.Ve
